04031nmm a2200589Ia 9780801461736DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014617367 a10.7591/97808014617362doi  a(DE-B1597)515460  a(OCoLC)1083626645  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a344.5694011 aMundlak, Guy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFading Corporatism :bIsrael's Labor Law and Industrial Relations in Transition /cGuy Mundlak. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b3 tables, 5 charts/graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the 1980s, industrial relations and labor law in Israel have rapidly changed from a European style of corporatism to a model of pluralism familiar to North America. The country's legal and industrial relations systems have become more decentralized, yet more intensively regulated; they are no longer centrally managed, but they do not fit the neoliberal model of a free market. In recent years, a dynamic system for voicing interests has evolved, granting more leeway to individuals, identity-based representation, and a flourishing civil society, but restraining effective collective representation. In Fading Corporatism, Guy Mundlak explains the changing nature of labor law and industrial relations in Israel and the seemingly paradoxical outcomes of transformation as played out in numerous spheres, including the law governing the recognition of trade unions and strikes; the emergence of a human rights regime; and the regulation of temporary work agencies, Palestinian workers from the occupied territories, and migrant workers. Placing the example of Israel in a conceptual framework that draws on the literature of corporatism, Mundlak offers a theoretical coupling of legal studies and industrial relations that will interest scholars and practitioners in both fields. Surveying legal developments from 1920 to the present, Fading Corporatism will also appeal to readers interested in the political, economic, and legal history of Israel. At the same time, Mundlak emphasizes the comparative implications of the Israeli case study. His account is particularly instructive for countries in which traditionally corporatist industrial and legal systems are experiencing similar pressures, such as the Netherlands, Austria, and Germany.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCorporate statexIsrael. 0aCorporate statezIsrael. 0aIndustrial relationsxIsrael. 0aIndustrial relationszIsrael. 0aLabor laws and legislationxIsrael. 0aLabor laws and legislationzIsrael. 4aLabor History. 4aLegal History & Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146173640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801461736423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801461736/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles